"\n## Problems\nLet $x$, $y$ and $z$ all exceed $1$ and let $w$ be a positive number such that $\\log_x w = 24$, $\\log_y w = 40$ and $\\log_{xyz} w = 12$. Find $\\log_z w$. Show that it is 060.\n\n## Informal proof\nThe [[logarithm]]ic notation doesn't tell us much, so we'll first convert everything to the equivalent exponential forms.\n\n$x^{24}=w$, $y^{40}=w$, and $(xyz)^{12}=w$. If we now convert everything to a power of $120$, it will be easy to isolate $z$ and $w$.\n\n$x^{120}=w^5$, $y^{120}=w^3$, and $(xyz)^{120}=w^{10}$.\n\nWith some substitution, we get $w^5w^3z^{120}=w^{10}$ and $\\log_zw=060$.\n\n## Formal statement\n```isabelle\ntheorem aime_1983_p1:\n  fixes x y z w :: nat\n  assumes ht : \"1 < x \\<and> 1 < y \\<and> 1 < z\"\n    and hw : \"0 \\<le> w\"\n    and h0 : \"ln w / ln x = 24\"\n    and h1 : \"ln w / ln y = 40\"\n    and h2 : \"ln w / ln (x * y * z) = 12\"\n  shows \"ln w / ln z = 60\"\n```\n\n## Structured informal proof\nStep 1: Convert the logarithmic equations to exponential form.\nStep 2: Raise each equation to the power of 120 to make the exponents of $w$ consistent.\nStep 3: Substitute the expressions for $x^{120}$ and $y^{120}$ into the equation for $(xyz)^{120}$.\nStep 4: Simplify the equation to isolate $z^{120}$ and $w$.\nStep 5: Convert the simplified equation back to logarithmic form to find $\\log_z w$.\n\n## Lemmas\n### Lemma 1\nA lemma showing the conversion between logarithmic and exponential forms would be useful.\n\n### Code 1\n```isabelle\nlemma log_exp_conversion:\n  fixes a b :: real\n  assumes \"a > 0\" \"b > 0\" \"a \u2260 1\"\n  shows \"log_a b = c \u27f7 a^c = b\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 2\nA lemma showing the properties of logarithms with respect to multiplication would be useful.\n\n### Code 2\n```isabelle\nlemma log_mult:\n  fixes a b c :: real\n  assumes \"a > 0\" \"b > 0\" \"c > 0\" \"a \u2260 1\"\n  shows \"log_a (b * c) = log_a b + log_a c\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 3\nA lemma showing the properties of logarithms with respect to powers would be useful.\n\n### Code 3\n```isabelle\nlemma log_power:\n  fixes a b c :: real\n  assumes \"a > 0\" \"b > 0\" \"a \u2260 1\"\n  shows \"log_a (b^c) = c * log_a b\"\n```\n\nThese lemmas will help in converting the logarithmic equations to exponential form, manipulating the exponential equations, and converting the final result back to logarithmic form."